<div id="review_2317147375" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2317147375" />
    <a title="Lancelot du Lac" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/78732453-lancelot-du-lac"><img alt="Lancelot du Lac" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1618132945p2/78732453.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2317147375?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lancelot du Lac" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lancelot du Lac" href="/user/show/78732453-lancelot-du-lac">Lancelot du Lac</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2317147375" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7039029289241378218">This book is a set of carefully selected short-stories, travelogues, novellas and personal experiences of Ruskin Bond. If I am to enlist some Indian authors whom a student reads (other than his academic textbooks), then Ruskin Bond and Chetan Bhagat would be on the top. (Although I find Chetan Bhagat&apos;s writing a bit mediocre as it reminds me of Indian soaps and sub-standard story lines which don&apos;t invoke any emotions and lack depth). On the other hand, Ruskin Bond&apos;s lucid and happy-go-lucky writ</span>
  <span id="freeText7039029289241378218" style="display:none">This book is a set of carefully selected short-stories, travelogues, novellas and personal experiences of Ruskin Bond. If I am to enlist some Indian authors whom a student reads (other than his academic textbooks), then Ruskin Bond and Chetan Bhagat would be on the top. (Although I find Chetan Bhagat's writing a bit mediocre as it reminds me of Indian soaps and sub-standard story lines which don't invoke any emotions and lack depth). On the other hand, Ruskin Bond's lucid and happy-go-lucky writing style leaves a lasting impression on our mind &amp; heart. Another reason that makes him so popular is that he abstains from using technical language, instead, he recounts everything in a layman's way. In spite of the clearly visible simplicity, his creations don't fail to arouse deep thoughts and invoke sweet &amp; sour memories. A child may enjoy Mr Bond's stories but on the other hand, a mature adult will find himself transported to his childhood days. Lastly, as I hail from the North Indian mountains, It is my opinion that no Indian author understands the mountains and mountain people better than him. When I read his travelogues about Garhwal, I felt teleported to the mountains. I felt the bright sun kissing my cheeks, at the same time I felt the cool breeze hitting my face.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7039029289241378218" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


